bug.short_desc: Marker to indicate method hiding

long_desc.thetext: If a class defines a static method with the same signature as a static method in a superclass then the class method hides the superclass' method. Like the overrides/implements upwards pointing arrows, it would be helpful to mark methods that hide superclass methods. This would provide feedback that could prevent bugs where the wrong method is inadvertantly called or mistyped.
Shadowing always depends on the scope you're in. I don't think we can render this as a element state. No plans for this, sorry.

I don't see how class method hiding relates to scope - I would have thought this was purely inheritence-based and almost identical to detecting overriding, with the difference being that both methods must be static (as in JLS3 8.4.8.2-3).
I filed this enhancement request because method hiding can go contrary to Java's expected behaviour (statically binding to declared type instead of dynamically to runtime type) but Eclipse does nothing to warn of this, even though there is feedback for shadowing variables and overriding (instance) methods. (I was caught out by this after casting an object and calling a static method on it which evaluated to one other than that which I expected - I originally thought attempting to override a static method would generate a compilation error until I realised I had sort of done this legally by accident).

OK, I think I see your point now. A compiler warning would make sense to warn the user of the potential behaviour change. A marker/decorator on the B.foo() declaration would act more informationally to confirm that the method does indeed hide A.foo() or as a subtle prompt: 'Did you mean to do that?', and presumably as a link back to A.foo() (in the same way that the override marker links to the method in the suerclass).
I think there is a case for the JDT to feed this information back to users, though I can see that there are potential arguments about the best way to do this.
I filed bug 150620 to suggest a new compiler warning for this scenario.

It looks like you are running some 3.2 bundles on a version of org.eclipse.osgi from 3.1. In 3.1 the Equinox framework (org.eclipse.osgi) did not properly verify the execution environment. We fixed this in 3.2 and we also moved the verification of the execution environment to resolve time so that we do not prevent bundles from being installed when their execution environment does not match.
Please run with the -noExit -console options. When it fails run the "ss" command at the osgi> prompt. This will list the installed bundles in your environment. Please post the output to this bug so we can evaluate what you have installed in your target. Thanks.
Also one way to work around this is to launch the 3.1 Equinox framework with the VM argument
-Dorg.osgi.framework.executionenvironment="OSGi/Minimum-1.0,OSGi/Minimum-1.1,JRE-1.1,J2SE-1.2,J2SE-1.3,J2SE-1.4"

Output of the ss command
Framework is launched.
id State Bundle 0 ACTIVE system.bundle_3.1.2 2 RESOLVED org.eclipse.update.configurator_3.1.0 3 ACTIVE org.eclipse.core.runtime_3.1.2

It looks like you are running the 3.1.2 equinox framework with a 3.2 configuration. How did you import all the 3.1 plugins into 3.2?
If you want to target an eclipse 3.1 platform then I would recommend setting your target platform to an eclipse 3.1.2 installation. You can do this at Window->Preferences->Plug-in Development->Target Platform. Under Location select the eclipse directory where you extracted eclipse 3.1.2. This should allow you to launch 3.1.2 eclipse from PDE in 3.2 eclipse.
Tom, just to be clear: under what circumstances does a plug-in with an EE not run properly against a 3.1 framework?

See bug 141744 and bug 140955 for similar issues.
There are two things that changed in Eclipse 3.2 WRT execution environment verification ...
1) We moved the execution environment verification from the install process to the resolve process (bug 111333)
2) We set the list of supported execution environments according the the java profile selected in osgi (bug 108271). Before we only set the execution environment to the currently running VM. For example on a 1.4.2 VM we would set it to only J2SE-1.4. It really should have been set to the complete set of EEs that a 1.4.2 VM supports (i.e. OSGi/Minimum-1.0,OSGi/Minimum-1.1,JRE-1.1,J2SE-1.2,J2SE-1.3,J2SE-1.4)
In 3.1 this results in installation failures when a bundle specifies an EE of J2SE-1.3 but the current VM is 1.4.2. This is because we did not set the running EE to a complete set of supported EEs for 1.4.2 AND we did the EE verification check at install time. The work around in 3.1 is to set the EE for the platform manually using the following configuration property for a 1.4.2 VM:
org.osgi.framework.executionenvironment="OSGi/Minimum-1.0,OSGi/Minimum-1.1,JRE-1.1,J2SE-1.2,J2SE-1.3,J2SE-1.4"
This worksforme. Please reopen if you are still having problems and provide the information requested in comment 3. Thanks.

bug.short_desc: WST seems to set java.net.Authenticator default for entire platform

long_desc.thetext:
I am involved in a project extending the Eclipse platform. One of the projects under my responsibility has to query a URL and to pass a generated proxy password. That password may expire occasionally which requires me to generate the password anew if the response tells "proxy authentication required". If this happens a popup apparently coming from the wst toolset asks for username and password. Obviously the handler for this has been set by utilizing java.net.Authenticator#setDefault(java.net.Auithenticator). This makes any alternative treatment by platform consumers obsolete. Eclipse should provide a more generic way to handle authentication in URL connections. In my opinion, a safeguarding API as proposed in my blog in the URL with this report should be provided by the platform.
Kindest Regards Richard

Richard, I agree with your remarks on the issues around statics and singletons, and have run into similar issues with other JRE unextensible singletons like URLStreamHandlerFactory (at least on earlier Eclipse platforms) and security Providers.
I'm returning this as a duplicate of RFE bug 88017, which is open against the Eclipse platform to move the entire internet settings component - proxy configuration, authentication handling and so forth - from WTP down to the platform.
When you wrote in your blog that you "wanted to ask for the user and to generate the password anew", are you looking for a way to customize the authentication behaviour specific to certain URL connections made by your connections without affecting the authentication behaviour associated with URL connections made by other components? If so, maybe the implementation of RFE bug 88017 needs to provide an extensible Authenticator into which components could plug-in their own handlers - a chain of sorts with some form of filtering. Apache Jakarta Commons HTTPClient provides a much more comprehensive and component-friendly mechanism, and perhaps could also be integrated into the Eclipse platform for components that choose to use it.
A few thoughts on safeguarding. We have often had to use similar techniques to performing so-called "safe" temporary changes to statics and singletons. Unfortunately, the safety of these techniques - via safeguarding API or otherwise - applies only to those components that are aware of the techniques and are able to use them responsibly, if at all. In particular, there are many cases of third-party non-Eclipse components that are integrated into the Eclipse platform and which have no knowledge of or ability use safeguarding API in the Eclipse platform. The Authenticator is particularly nasty since it may get invoked by virtue of any Eclipse or non-Eclipse component opening a URL connection. If different components require different authentication behaviour, then all components making URL connections would require the ability to lock out changes to the Authenticator for the duration of their use of URL connections. The programming complexity and performance implications get really nasty, particularly for longer running, URL-intensive Eclipse or non-Eclipse (third-party) components.
Perhaps the answers lies with the JRE to deprecate and replace some of the nastier singletons by more component/bundle-friendly mechanisms?
Just thinking aloud here.
Thanks - CB.
*** This bug has been marked as a duplicate of 88017 ***

Dear Chris,
thanks for your evaluation. Just a few remarks:
Generally, I found bug #4941958 on the Sun bug database: http://bugs.sun.com/bugdatabase/view_bug.do?bug_id=4941958
This would solve the problem for everyone in a fashionable manner. I don't know how one could support this bug so that it becomes fixed.
Yes, I want to change authentication for specific URLConnections (HttpURLConnection to be more precise).
With safeguarding, I agree with you that any developer vould spoil it. On the other hand, I have some experience with jdbc and pooled connections there. As with any pooled resource you have the problem, that the client coding must release the resource somehow to get it back to the pool (in jdbc this means closing the connection). So there are situations where client coding has to follow a loosely coupled contract which cannot be enforced by the API being called. For that reason I think that a safeguarded approach would be better than nothing.
Kindest Regards Richard

bug.short_desc: Feature request: add BaseAgent.sendData(int, byte[]) in Java API

long_desc.thetext:
To be able to send binary data via DataChannel It is need additional Java API method BaseAgent.sendData(int, byte[])
Existing method BaseAgent.sendData(int, char[]) can't be used in binary data transfer since char is Unicode 2 bytes data type and can be used in strings transfer only.
Deferring since cannot be contained in 4.3
Not yet triaged

Created an attachment (id=66283) Introduce JNI implementation of sendData(int, byte[]) and fix sendData(int, char[]) bug
This is a patch for both Bug 150217 and Bug 150216.

Created an attachment (id=66284) Introduce SendData(int, byte[]) Java implementation
This is a patch for both Bug 150217 and Bug 150216.
The patches are submitted. Samson, could you review the patches, please?

Hi Stanislav. Is there a reason of changing the IBaseAgent interface at this time? Is there a possiblity of breaking existing agent if we do so now?
BTW this is not targeted to 4.4 and is not in plan as an enhancement. I would not suggest checking this in now until this enhancement is approved since this might be an API-breaking change.

Hi all,
You have all my apologies if I interfere in your work processes, but I read the patches attached by Stanislav, and two facts are clear to me :
1. The correction of the bug #150216, included in the patch, does not affect the API.
2. The modification does not change the API, it just adds a new function without any modification to the existing ones.
So it would be great if the patch could be committed shortly, or a least if it could be broken in two. If so, the corrective part of the patch could be committed and the bug 150216 would be closed, at least.
Anyway, to develop an Java agent with this bug is not really clean.
Best regards.
Marc
Resolving as fixed

bug.short_desc: Select DataSource with report Engine

long_desc.thetext:
hi,
i use Birt 2.1 with eclipse 3.2.
i got this in my birt-xml-file:
<data-sources> <oda-data-source extensionID="org.eclipse.birt.report.data.oda.jdbc" name="Data Source" id="39"> <text-property name="displayName">Data Source</text-property> <property name="odaDriverClass">org.postgresql.Driver</property> <property name="odaURL">jdbc:postgresql://localhost:5432/foo</property> <property name="odaUser">foo_user</property> <encrypted-property name="odaPassword">adfadsf</encrypted-property> <property name="odaJndiName">java:foo.foo.foo</property> </oda-data-source> </data-sources>
I want to generate the html-report in my web-application. So i use the report engine. All works fine. Now the problem:
When i use Eclipse for creating the birt-xml-file, i specify the jdbc-connection (as you see in my code). Moreover i specify jndi-name (as you see above). When i use the report engine, the jdbc-connection is used first. if it fails, the jndi connection will be used. I want to always the jndi-connection when i generate the html page. How can i say the report engine, to use the jndi connection first? Is this possilble? (The ugly workaround would be, to change a property (e.g. "odaURL") in the xml file, to make sure, that the jdbc-connection fails)
-- orkus9

There is a mis-understanding of the JNDI usage in your description.
The correct sequence as described in Bugzilla #131662: If the oda.jdbc data source property "odaJndiName" is specified with a non-empty value, it will first attempt to use the named JNDI resource to obtain a java.sql.Connection. If it fails for any reason, then it will fall back to get a new jdbc connection directly from the jdbc driver, specified in the "odaURL" property.

When i change the username, host to XXX, no JNDI-Connection could be found. It seems so, that birt is not using the jndi connection first (see logfile). Now the miracle: When i change the jdbc-startdart-connection values like this:
private static void dropJDBCSettings(IReportRunnable design) { final List contents = design.getDesignHandle().getModuleHandle().getAllDataSources(); for(int i = 0; i < contents.size(); i++) { OdaDataSourceHandle dataSource = (OdaDataSourceHandle) contents.get(i); try { Object o = dataSource.getProperty("odaUser"); if(o != null) { dataSource.setProperty("odaUser", ""); } o = dataSource.getProperty("odaURL"); if(o != null) { dataSource.setProperty("odaURL", "xxx"); } } catch (SemanticException e) { throw new IllegalStateException(e.toString()); } } }
Now the JNDI connection works fine. All i have done is: adoUser = ""; odaURL="xxx";
When the jndi connection is used first, why i get the error (like in the logfile below). I am totally confused. For me its not logical.
Please help me. :-(
- orkus9

It looks like this issue is the result of an incompatible change we made in BIRT 2.0 in report parameters. In BIRT 1.x, default value for a report parameter is a Javascript expression (therefore a literal string must be quoted, such as "7|D|1|D" to make it a valid expression). In BIRT 2.0 and beyond, the default values are now literals (expressions are no longer supported). Literal string values no longer require quoting.
The bug is in the ROM upgrade code. When the 1.x report design is opened, DE should have removed the double quotes around the string default values for parameters.

bug.short_desc: Flag a missing EE header

long_desc.thetext:
After installing the plugin eZing Builder (http://sourceforge.net/projects/ezingbuilder), I couldn't open the editor. I always got "ClassNotFoundException".
The root cause was that I was running Eclipse with Java 1.4 but the plugin contains classes which are compiled against Java 1.5.
I'd like to see two enhancements:
- When a plugin contains classes which require Java 1.5, the builder in PDE should disallow to export it without the necessary Execution Environment.
- When the classloader can't load a class because it requires a different Java runtime, it should say so (instead of "The editor class could not be instantiated. This usually indicates that the editor's class name was mistyped in plugin.xml.").
This second enhancement is probably part of Equinox:
java.lang.ClassNotFoundException: com.neusoft.ezingbuilder.designer.editors.HtmlFckDesignerMultiPageEditor at org.eclipse.osgi.framework.internal.core.BundleLoader.findClass(BundleLoader.java:407) at org.eclipse.osgi.framework.internal.core.BundleLoader.findClass(BundleLoader.java:352) at org.eclipse.osgi.internal.baseadaptor.DefaultClassLoader.loadClass(DefaultClassLoader.java:83) at java.lang.ClassLoader.loadClass(Unknown Source)

This type of error would not happen if the author of the plug-in you are using had specified the required execution environment (see http://wiki.eclipse.org/index.php/Execution_Environments and http://lenettoyeur-on-eclipse.blogspot.com/2006/07/setting-bundle-requiredexecutionenviro.html) You should open a bug against the author of the component.
Moving to the UI team to see if they can report a better problem. Note that this could tie in with the serviceability solution.

> if the author of the plug-in you are using > had specified the required execution environment
Yes, you are correct but the same would happen if I accidentially added a JAR, which was compiled with Java 1.5 for some reason, to a plugin.
As long as I run Eclipse with Java 1.5, I wouldn't notice. Therefore my request that PDE should check for these kinds of errors and complain when someone tries to export such a broken plugin.

>Therefore my request that PDE should check for these kinds of errors and >complain when someone tries to export such a broken plugin.
Not sure what you mean by "checking for such errors". The plug-in is not broken. If it were, the export would fail.
The plug-in just does not specify an execution environment. No need for PDE to interfere here. an execution environment is useful/recommended, but it is optional, and not having it is not an error.
If the behaviour you see at runtime (ie. the classloading error) is mystifying, then I suggest you reopen and move the bug to Equinox for better error reporting.

As it is now, Eclipse requires Java 1.4, so plugins cannot expect to have Java 1.5.
On the other hand, it's perfectly possible to create plugins which *require* Java 1.5 without an execution environment.
From my point of view, that's like digging a hole and waiting for someone to fall into it.
As Java 1.5 becomes more and more widespread, more and more plugins will break.
So, as I said in my first comment, PDE should only allow to create plugins without exec env as long as they don't need features which are outside the default exec env (probably Java SDK 1.4).
I'll create a second bug report for Equinox so we can keep these issues apart.

I see what you are saying, but PDE can't police the plug-ins and introspect the code in real time to make sure you have an EE defined if you are using a Java5 feature.
Plus, your code may have a path that uses Java5 features, but that path may only get executed in very specific scenarios, so this plug-in would run just fine with 1.4 under normal circumstances.
This is all very subjective. That is why PDE should remain out of the way, and it is up to the owner of the plug-in to specify the Execution Environment if one is needed.

Of course, there might be corner cases but generally, all class files in a JAR will have been compiled with the same Java version, so checking the bytecode version of just one file in every jar should be enough to generate a warning.
Right now, many plugin developers are unaware that the issue even exists. As a user, I must manually check that the plugin will run even though Eclipse would provide the means.
Maybe for 3.2.1, you could enforce the EE a bit more, ie. generate a warning when it's not set? This way, the person who should know (the developer) can make an educated guess instead of putting this issue on the shoulders of the users.
Wasn't there a FindBugs-like thing for plugins? I thought I remembered something but I'm not sure.

As mentioned above, a missing EE header is not an error. However, it may be desirable by some teams/companies to enforce having it. So this seems like a reasonable request, and we already have a flag for EE validation in the plug-in compiler preferences.
I'll reopen and rename the bug report to reflect the new focal point.
This is certainly is not a 3.2.x issue though. It will be evaluated for 3.3 and it will depend on how much we want to enforce having an EE in manifests.

The real issue here still needs to be addressed at the platform level which is to give a good error message instead of a class not found exception.
The warning at the PDE level is just a nice-to-have.
*** Bug 189580 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***
*** Bug 189579 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***
This is a fairly straightforward warning / quickfix Adam.

Chris, what did you have in mind for the recommended quickfix. The developer still needs to make an educated decision on the EE level they want to choose. Would the quickfix list all the valid EEs a developer can choose?

Simply a configurable problem marker (warning by default) that tells people that they don't have an EE set. The quickfix can simply set the EE header and let you autocomplete it (which you can do already). We could be smarter and even put down an initial EE as part of the quickfix based on your default JRE and its current perfect match EE.

bug.short_desc: Code assist for unresolved local variables

long_desc.thetext: As discussed at the JDT Summit.
Collect potential identifiers in the completion scanner.
We could want to only collect identifiers not following a dot or other characters never prefixing a single name ref.
Created an attachment (id=52315) Proposed fix

Released for 3.3 M3.
Test added CompletionTests#testCompletionVariableName16() -> testCompletionVariableName32()
Potential identifiers are collected from the end of the local variable to the end of the enclosing block. Identifiers following a dot are ignored. Identifiers followed by a ( or { are ignored. Identifier starting with an uppercase are ignored because most of the type it would be a type reference and not an unresolved name. Identifiers that would add name conflicts with another variable or field are ignored.
The source are only scanned and parsed with standard recovery (no statements recovery) to avoid to do too costly operation as binding resolution and statements recovery.

Created an attachment (id=52522) Addionnal fix
The released fix performances aren't good enough. This patch improve performance and limit to 100 the number of parsed lines.

bug.short_desc: Invalid pageNumber at repeated group header in PDF output

long_desc.thetext:
Setup: Report with table group. Option "Repeat header" is activated. Expression of group header is defined as following: "Current page number " + pageNumber PDF output of report (table) spans over multiple pages.
Expected outcome of table group header within PDF output at page 2: "Current page number 2"
Resulting outcome of table group header within PDF output at page 2: "Current page number 1"
as we has support the page-number as the auto-text, so can we remove the page-number in the onCreate/onRender time? (The page-number can only be accessed in onPageBreak).

(In reply to comment #1) > as we has support the page-number as the auto-text, so can we remove the > page-number in the onCreate/onRender time? (The page-number can only be > accessed in onPageBreak).
onPageBreak() is only triggered for when page is break because of a page break setting in the design, correct? page break due to master page size limit will not triggered onPageBreak(), or will it?
I agree that we might need to remove the pageNumber from the onCreate() script, because the page number could change depends on the final output format of the report. The pageNumber in the onCreate() script will not be correct for certain output format.
on the other hand, in onRender(), the page number should be supported?
Can we review this as part of the overall scripting API enhancement?

Does this mean we should make a variable of a element in script configurable? For example, when editting script for "OnCreate" method, "pageNumber" is invisible in the help context of "this". And it comes to be visible when editting script for "OnRender"/"OnPageBreak"?

suggest to remove the pagenumber property from "this" in onCreate/onPageBreak, and have it at onRender().
I think onPageBreak() can not have the correct page number neither during report creation time, because it only accounts for logical page break, it doesn't account for paper-size trigged new pages.
Engine team controls the script
Engine decide if they could support this.

Suggest to also remove the pageNumber property in OnRender script. Because at render time, the pageNumber is also uncertain. For example, layout engine starts to render a image. First the onRender script is executed, current page number is n. But this image may be put into n+1 page due to the page size limitation.

Is it correct that when onRender() is executed, the current page is n? I think it is correct to have the value of this.pageNumber to be n. I think it is ok that some or all of the "this" will be render to page n+1, but if it starts at "n", this.pagenumber can be "n". Table report item is another example that when onRender is triggered, its pagenumber is n, but a table could span from page n to m.
Changing on behalf of Renuka
suggest to allow pageNumber in onRender but not onCreate and onPrepare events.
add the "plan" key word for release planning.

Procedure: - Add several CVS projects to the workspace. Ensure that the CVS project decoration is applied and in view. - On one of the CVS projects select TEAM >> DISCONNECT to remove the association from CVS. This should remove the CVS decoration from the project elements displayed.
Actual Results: - The decoration for all the CVS projects flash (is temporarily removed and then replaced) as the disconnect action for a single project commenses.
--------- I tried to replicate this behavior in the base Eclipse and it does not seem to be a problem.
Does this happen in WTP or in a product based on WTP?
WTP I believe.

This defect system should only be used to resolve defects that originate in WTP.
OK

bug.short_desc: License agreement has text and fields overlapping

long_desc.thetext:
Opened for IBM (Rodolfo Napoles) :
The SUN license agreement screen displayed after clicking OK to read the license agreement shows text and field overlaping.
Steps: 1. Install WTP 1.5 2. From the main menu select File->New Project->Web->Dynamic Web Project, and click Next. Call the project MyDynamicWebProject, keep all default settings and click next until Finish. 3. After pression Finish, a dialog is displayed asking you to read the LIcense agreement to be able to move on, say OK 4. the License agreement is displayed with a search label and text fiel overap over the "Sun Developer Network" title

This is a limitation of the remote license file from Sun. We'd need to reformat the file in order to correct this. This will necessitate including the license file in our WTP distribution.
Janet, is there any legal problem in extracting the text from the Sun license found at [1], creating a text only file that includes the text from the license agreement and including the text file in the WTP distribution?
[1]http://developers.sun.com/license/berkeley_license.html

(In reply to comment #1) > This is a limitation of the remote license file from Sun. We'd need to reformat > the file in order to correct this. This will necessitate including the license > file in our WTP distribution. > > Janet, is there any legal problem in extracting the text from the Sun license > found at [1], creating a text only file that includes the text from the license > agreement and including the text file in the WTP distribution? > > [1]http://developers.sun.com/license/berkeley_license.html > I don't see any difficulty in proceeding. Janet
This bug is in the J2EE schema and DTD definitions contained in the org.eclipse.jst.j2ee plug-in.
Created an attachment (id=47991) Patch for org.eclipse.jst.j2ee that includes the cleaned up license file.

Created an attachment (id=47992) Screenshot of the cleaned up license in the license dialog.
Janet, this screenshot shows what the license will look like in Eclipse. The previous attachment is a patch that shows a change that includes a new berkeley_license.html file that I created from the text on http://developers.sun.com/license/berkeley_license.html.
John - Does this look to solve your problem?
Yep, that looks good Lawrence.
Fix released to 1.5.1 on 20060816.
Closing.

bug.short_desc: [typing] Pasting a contents inside a string to get string concatenation doesn't work if the string is not an empty string

long_desc.thetext:
Using 3.2, copy some code. Open a new empty string. Paste your code and it ends up as string concatenation.
Now copy some code. Open a string which is not an empty string. Select the contents of the string except the starting and ending double quote and paste your code. The code is not seen as a string concatenation.
Fixed in HEAD. Available in builds > N20060721-0010.

bug.short_desc: Use unique message identifiers

long_desc.thetext:
You can tell I have an IBM product background. An example would be something like: AJCL0001I AspectJ Weaver Version 1.5.0 built on Tuesday Dec 20, 2005 at 12:05:54 GMT .Unique alphanumeric IDs have a number of benefits: 1. They act as a key when moving messages to a separate text file. We already have such a file for the weaver but use a short name instead for the key. The ID could be combined with the key 2. The combination of an ID and separate file facilitate message translation. This has already been done for AJDT (Bug 112320 Translations for AJDT). We may also be required to do this for AspectJ if we become an Eclipse Tools project especially as many of our messages are now issued at runtime and will be seen by a wider range of users. 3. Even if messages are not issued in a particular national language an ID can be easier to find amongst a host of other messages produced by a complex system be it a build or runtime situation. Messages are often split if multiple threads are involved. 4. Unique IDs aid testing and would allow AspectJ to be tested with non-English message files. Today if the text of a message changes tests that look for the message may also need to change. With a message ID the test can specify which one it is looking for an optionally any inserts. 5. By using the right convention it should be easier to quickly identify which component (compiler, weaver, loadtime, runtime, ) issued the message.
I have hinted at a possible format for AspectJ message IDs in my example but I am open to suggestions. The only requirements are the it should be unique, compact and identify the origin of the message. Above we have AJC=AspectJ, L=loadtime, 0001 and I=info. You could the have C=compiler, A=ajde and W=weaver. Also E=error, W=warning and V=weaveInfo.

bug.short_desc: Non-conformant copyright date ranges in EMFT Sources

long_desc.thetext:
The EMFT OCL, Query, Transaction, and Validation projects all have numerous source files (.java, .xml, .properties, etc.) specifying date ranges with a hyphen ('-') rather than a comma (','). These must be fixed to use a comma.
Find the files in question by performing a workspace search for the following regex:
copyright.*\d\s*-\s*\d
in all source files.
Fix is committed to the R1_0_maintenance branch.

bug.short_desc: Correct dates copyright notices

long_desc.thetext:
JET contains numerous copyright notices of the form:
* Copyright (c) 2002-2004 IBM Corporation and others.
According to IBM legal, they should use a comma (,) instead of a dash (-). The correct form of the above copyright is:
* Copyright (c) 2002, 2004 IBM Corporation and others.
Changes committed to CVS.
Fixed in build M200607131358 (0.7.1)

bug.short_desc: JVM crash when using SWT_AWT bridge in XP

long_desc.thetext:
For the past six months I have been trying to debug a JVM crash in my RCP application without any success.
We are currently using an AWT-based terminal emulation program, incorporated into our RCP-based program using the SWT_AWT bridge class, in order to allow access my company's existing green-screen system. Our users have complained about unpredictable JVM crashes that occur while they are navigating through the green-screen system. We know for a fact that this issue is not caused by the terminal emulator because for over a year-and-a-half, our users used a stand-alone version of this exact same product without any problems. We are currently talking to the terminal emulator vendors about the issue, but they are starting to doubt that there's anything they can do about it.
The following three sample stack traces were generated by three different users doing three different things in the terminal emulator. The only consistent fact about this bug is that it occurs seemingly at random while they are switching from screen to screen, but that is the only commonality between them. All but one of our users are using JVM 1.5.0_06, one of these logs comes from the user using JVM 1.5.0_03. Any help or suggestions would be greatly appreciated.

bug.short_desc: Provide context for LTW verbose messages

long_desc.thetext: The verbose LTW messages currently provide information about AspectJ version, what aspects are registered and which classes are woven as well as lower level details such as class loader identity. However in a large system with multiple weaving classloaders messages can become interleaved and it is impossible to determine which classloader/weaver is involved. This enhancement would use the IWeavingContext to add an identifier, by default the classloader ID, to every message.

I have committed the first implementation of this feature. The only change to the externals is a new method IWeavingContext.getId() that allows users to specify a short suffix for all messages produced during LTW. If you build and run the LTW sample you will now get:

bug.short_desc: CanonicalEditPolicy should update diagram correctly if same model element could be represented by different diagram nodes

long_desc.thetext:
Currently CanonicalEditPolicy can update diagram contents if new element was added/removed, but can not update diagram contents if some properties of the element was changed and corresponding properties are important for a viewmapping of the element. In other words, once element was added to the diagram, it can not change view representation anymore.
In the same time, desired usecase is the following:
Same domain model element should be visualized in a different way (different views should be created for it with different semantic hints + different child views) depending on the property stored in model. For example, "show children" domain model element property should be responsible for showing/not showing children compartment and child elements in it.
Currently CanonicalEditPolicy does not allow to implement this functionality without huge changes in its logic because it has getSemanticChildrenList() method returning a set of EObjects. This method will be used to get semantic children of this domain model element and then create new views for the elements from this list which has no view associated or remove views which has element associated, but not returned by this method. Not way to remove old view + add new one for an element returned in this list, but changed since last diagram opening so view representation of it should be changed as well.

Proposed solution is to return some wrapper around semantic model object from getSemanticChildrenList() method. This wrapper could be similar to LinkDescription class suggested by me as a fix for the request: https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=133505.
NodeDescriptor should hold semantic model instance and SemanticHint in addition. Different SemanticHints and the same model elements would be contained in this wrapper for "show children" == true/false in an example above, so CanonicalEditPolicy will be able to recognize that viewmapping of the element was changed, call ViewProvider to create new view, move all applicable values of assigned view styles to newly created view (positions, colors, e.t.c) and remove old view.
In the described situation EClass.isInterface() == true/false will be represented by different diagram nodes -> different semantic hints. So, "matching" process will be able to distinguish between isInterface() == true and false and as a result, old diagram node will be removed and new one created.

Attaching e-mail discussion with Steven.
Alex Shatalin: Same domain model element could be represented by different EditParts. We have a usecase then the same model element could be represented by different nodes (EditParts) on diagram. Example: on ECore diagram interfaces (EClass.isInterface() == true) should be shown as circle without children, but classes (EClass.isInterface() == false) should be shown as a rectangles with child elements. I suppose that CanonicaEditPolicy is responsible for removing "circle" and adding "rectangle" if .isInterface() was changed in the semantic model, from the other side it is not possible now. Imagine that we have a diagram with one EClass on it. This EClass.isInterface() == true and it is shown as a circle now. User can close diagram and using some external editor change isInterface() to "false". CanonicalEditPolicy will be called on reopening this diagram, getSemanticChildrenList() will return EObject representing instance of EClass which will be perfectly matched with an EObject stored inside Node instance representing this EClass on a diagram currently. As a result, diagram will not be changed and "circle" representation of EClass will not be replaced by "square" one. v
Steven Shaw: I would think this would be the responsibility of the EditPart service and/or the View service providers for your plug-in. Based on the specific semantic property a different provider would kick-in. The CanonicalEditPolicy need not know about how a different EditPart or View is created based on a dynamic property state. The proper way if the state changes would be to have the EditPart listening to this property and then calling handleMajorSemanticChange when handling the event which essentially forces recreation of the EditPart. To recreate the View, this would be more difficult. First you'd have to evaluate if it is necessary to recreate the view is the position, style information still relevant for the new shape? If not then, the EditPart could still listen to this event and then delete the view from the parent diagram using the ViewUtil.destroy(view). Then the EditPart will be destroyed automatically and the CanonicalEditPolicy would receive an event that the view was deleted and would invoke a refresh.
Alex Shatalin: I can not agree with you in this point. I would say that in a generic situation we should recreate a view to handle such changes just because different representations of the element could have different styles associated with it, different semantic hints.. So I would say that there should be two different types of views to handle this usecase and ViewProvider should be called to create new view in this situation.
Concerning the possibility to place synchronization code into the EditPart corresponding code will not be called if diagram was not opened before changing semantic model (e.g. changes was done in the EMF generated tree editor) as a result, view will not be removed BTW, I do not see the problem to place this code into CanonicalEditPolicy. You correctly said that CanonicalEditPolicy do not know anything about the process of creation of View/EditParts this is a responsibility of corresponding ServiceProviders, from the other side currently CanonicalEditPolicy contains the code which enumerates existing Views, semantic model elements and try to make an intersection between these two Sets to select set of views which should be removed and set of elements to create new views. If well try to handle two different types of views, each could be associated with the same semantic model element well found that semantic element is not enough to correctly calculate this intersection. AFAIK, additional property semantic hint was attached to the view to handle this situation. So, my suggestion is to take into account semantic element + semantic hint while performing this intersection in CanonicalEditPolicy. This could be implemented in a different ways: a) return the pair semantic element + semantic hint form getSemanticChildrenList method b) by introducing one more protected boolean matches(View view, EObject semanticElement) into CanonicalEditPolicy. This method could return true by default.
Good question is a question about View Styles. I would say that currently we can try to move all the applicable styles from old view to new (again in CanonicalEditPolicy) but this again could be a responsibility of concrete subclasses of CanonicalEditPolicy.
I suppose that you have a legacy code which should be adopted and it could be a problem to perform these changes, but you see we can do it in most appropriate way even to try to save compatibility. Please, let me know what you think about all this.
Steven Shaw: Is it expected that these multiple View types for the same semantic element could live in the same container at the same time? Or are they mutually exclusive? i.e. based on a user action, the views transform into a different view. If so, what persists the user property that makes this state change? Intuitively this should be a Style on the diagram View (global), or perhaps a user preference. Or can these different view types exists together on the diagram based on a Style stored in the view itself?
Alex Shatalin: I keep in mind ECore diagram: association/aggregation links (containment attribute of EReference semantic model element) or EClasses with different value of interface attribute. So, my answers are: - these two different views could co-exists on the same diagram in the same moment. - the property could not be stored in view. Ok, it could be copied to view, but original property seems to be a property in semantic model.
Steven Shaw: I'll let Mohammed evaluate this further. Perhaps there is some accommodation needed in the CanonicalEditPolicy api to make this possible. In principle, this should still be the responsibility of the ViewProvider and/or EditPartProviders to differentiate the view / figures that are created based on the semantic attributes or context. I recommend logging a bugzilla so that a thread of discussion can be tracked.
Can we solve this problem in 2.0 M1?

bug.short_desc: [api] SystemRegistry.createHost() should allow specifying subsystem IDs

long_desc.thetext:
The service discovery process discovers a number of services from a specific host. The current createHost() implementations do not allow registering multiple services from a specific host unless they are part of a static list.
As a way of getting a unique identifier from each service, the extension point subSystemConfiguration id parameter can be used. It is what I'm using at the moment for service identification.
At the moment only 1 host can be created per discovered service, and it's not consistent with the rest of RSE hosts (this behaviour can be seen at the end of the movie in https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/attachment.cgi?id=45747)
To be able to create a host containing the selected and configured discovered services a new API in ISystemRegistry would be necessary. It could be something like:
public IHost createHost(String[] susbSystemConfigurationId, String connectionName, String hostName, String description)

Could you please outline an algorithm, what you'd expect the new API method to accomplish? - I'm surprised that you don't want to see the SystemType part of the method call.
So what the method could do, is scan all given subSystemConfigurations, and create the intersection of systemType for all. - What to do if the intersection is empty? - Then no host can be created. - What if the intersection contains more than 2 systemTypes? - Then the result of the call is ambiguous.
For me, it looks like the task can only be accomplished with user interaction. First get the list of possible systemTypes
/** Return the list of system types that support _all_ subSystems */ ISystemType[] getSupportedSystemTypes(String []subSystemConfigurationId)
Then let the user choose a specific one, create the host, and once the host is created select the proper services for those subsystems that have a selection of services (I have no idea how that could be accomplished).
Or am I misunderstanding? - Please elaborate.

(In reply to comment #1) > Could you please outline an algorithm, what you'd expect the new API method to > accomplish? - I'm surprised that you don't want to see the SystemType part of > the method call. > > So what the method could do, is scan all given subSystemConfigurations, and > create the intersection of systemType for all. > - What to do if the intersection is empty? - Then no host can be created. > - What if the intersection contains more than 2 systemTypes? - Then the result > of the call is ambiguous. > > For me, it looks like the task can only be accomplished with user interaction. > First get the list of possible systemTypes > > /** Return the list of system types that support _all_ subSystems */ > ISystemType[] getSupportedSystemTypes(String []subSystemConfigurationId) > > Then let the user choose a specific one, create the host, and once the host is > created select the proper services for those subsystems that have a selection > of services (I have no idea how that could be accomplished). > > Or am I misunderstanding? - Please elaborate. >
The list of available susbsystem ids can is available from the extension registry as:
Vector supportedServicesType = new Vector(); IExtensionPoint ep = Platform.getExtensionRegistry().getExtensionPoint("org.eclipse.rse.ui","subsystemConfiguration"); IConfigurationElement[] ce = ep.getConfigurationElements(); for (int i = 0; i < ce.length; i++) { String id = ce[i].getAttribute("id"); if(id!=null) supportedServicesType.add(id); }
The remote server should advertise services matching those subsystem ids, so RSE is capable to recognise them and match them with their subssytem plugin implementation.
Once received the services, the user should be able to select the received service matching one of the id contained in supportedServicesType. And after selecting the services, it should be possible to create new host based on the list of supported and selected services rather than using the systemType, as we are not based on a deterministic list of services.
The systemType ("Discovery") should only be necessary to start the service discovery wizard, but the created services might be a list of the available ones.

Thanks for your explanation - but you are not answering the original question.
Imagine that discovery found a single service, FTP. And is able to match it against subsystem configuration, ftp.files. The list of systemTypes supported by ftp.files is "Linux;Unix;Windows".
Which one of the three should createHost() choose?
The point is, that discovered services do not identify the systemType uniquely. There must be some user interaction to pick a unique systemType.
Do you have an idea what this could look like API-wise?

> Imagine that discovery found a single service, FTP. > And is able to match it against subsystem configuration, ftp.files. > The list of systemTypes supported by ftp.files is "Linux;Unix;Windows". > > Which one of the three should createHost() choose?
The idea of service discovery is that discovered services are not linked to a specific host, so the host type (systemType) should be only needed for the displayed icon.
> The point is, that discovered services do not identify the systemType uniquely. > There must be some user interaction to pick a unique systemType.
The discovered machine characteristics might be specified as: * generic "Discovery" systemType for discovered services ? * part of the discovery protocol ? * user selection from a list of available systemType ? * ... ?
> Do you have an idea what this could look like API-wise?
After the discovery process, the new hosts (containing the selected services) have to be created somehow. At the moment it is not possible since the systemType forces a list of services to be created. To avoid that, the list of the services have to be available, also the systemType, mainly for the icon to be displayed, have to be provided to createHost()
What do you think about an API such as:
public IHost createHost(String systemType, String[] susbSystemConfigurationId, String connectionName, String hostName, String description)

(In reply to comment #4)
> The idea of service discovery is that discovered services are not linked to a > specific host, so the host type (systemType) should be only needed for the > displayed icon.
This is a good idea, but unfortunately it is not (yet) quite true. For instance, in CommandsViewPage line 374: if(...cmdSubSystem.getHost().getSystemType().equals("Windows")) EnvironmentVariablesPromptDialog line 114: if (systemType.equals("Windows"))
There are many more places where the systemType is explicitly used to make some decisions (just search for String "Windows"). I agree that this is not a good idea at all for discovered services - it would be better to base decisions like the ones mentioned, on properties that can be set or reset in IHost.
In the long term, when we want to move towards a service oriented architecture, this is likely what we need to do; then, it would make sense to have a sepecial systemType "Discovery" that would be the container for _all_ discovered services.
While we are not yet there, we'll need to explicitly set a "proper" systemType. Could it be part of discovery, that a proper systemType is also detected? Could discovery find out if a remote system is of "Windows", "Linux" or "Other" type?
If not, then I'd vote for user interaction: Have the user pick a systemType from a list of "possible" systemTypes (i.e. those that support most discovered services).
> What do you think about an API such as: > > public IHost createHost(String systemType, String[] susbSystemConfigurationId, > String connectionName, String hostName, String description)
The problem here is that you are missing out on other properties like the defaultUserId. I'd see two alternatives for the new API:
(a) keep the createHost() methods as they are now, but add possibilities to _modify_ the already created IHost configuration later on. Or,
(b) Get rid of the current SystemRegistry.createHost(... ISystemNewConnectionWizardPage[] ...) signature in favor of something new that allows setting the subsystems and services properly.
I'm in favor of (b) since I find it awkward anyway that a non-UI class like SystemRegistry has some knowledge of WizardPages. Looks like this should be refactored anyway.
Increased to P2 since this is blocking for Javier
not critical - lowering priority

In order to make easier adopting service discovery to the community, I would suggest discovering system types instead of subsystem id's, as it may be easier to adopt.
At the moment we have FTP and SSH, that are subsystems, but also mapped as system types, so I would propose linking the remotely advertised services with the available system types.
It would work for FTP and SSH as simple services, but also would allow advertising dstore servers. So, with the current RSE, we would be able to discover the following services through DNS-SD :
* Daytime * FTP * Linux * SSH * Unix * Windows
Going for this solution would make easier using service discovery and this bug could be removed.

The current autodetect solution is not flexible enough to provide dynamic creation of hosts with discovered services. So this api change on IHost is required and it's stopping autodetect improvements for RSE 2.0
incrementing the priority to P2.

Javier, I'm working on adding methods in SystemRegistry to be able to create a host without creating the subsystems, and other methods to add/remove subsystems from a host.
I do have a question though. How would the discovery component handle subsystem types that we do not "know" about, i.e. not SSH, FTP or datastore. Note that subsystems are registered against system types. So if we're going to have a "discovery" system type, a new subsystem type will have to register itself against this system type for you to be able to create it for a discovery host.
Also, will you be adding the "discovery" system type in your plugin, as well as registering the existing subsystem types (SSH, FTP, dstore) against this "discovery" system type? I don't think it can be done in the base RSE plugins since they don't know about the "discovery" system type.

(In reply to comment #10) > How would the discovery component handle subsystem > types that we do not "know" about, i.e. not SSH, FTP or datastore. Note that > subsystems are registered against system types. So if we're going to have a > "discovery" system type, a new subsystem type will have to register itself > against this system type for you to be able to create it for a discovery host.
Wouldn't it be possible when creating the host, specify the subsystem IDs that are going to be attached to it ? Another solution would be create an empty "discovery" host and then add the discovered subsystems by ID using the new API.
> Also, will you be adding the "discovery" system type in your plugin, as well as > registering the existing subsystem types (SSH, FTP, dstore) against this > "discovery" system type? I don't think it can be done in the base RSE plugins > since they don't know about the "discovery" system type.
I would prefer doing it dynamically, so if somebody adds their own subsystem, they can use service discovery without having to register in against the "discovery" system type.

> (In reply to comment #10) > Wouldn't it be possible when creating the host, specify the subsystem IDs that > are going to be attached to it ?
I think this is related to bug 173265.
The point is that in "old" RSE, the subsystems had some implicit knowledge about the systemTypes, which was also used that in if() clauses etc - see the description of bug 150498 for details. Subsystems could be registered against system types only statically.
But nowadays, we have some "standard" subsystems which work against any TCP/IP connection (ftp, ssh, others in the future). For these, the systemType should be able to specify what subsystems it can deal with - see bug 173265. In addition to the static association, the association of systemType <-> subsystem should also be possible at runtime even if no static association in plugin.xml is there. Users should be able to choose what subsystems they think are compatible with their systemType, even without the static association.
The static association will still make sense to influence the new connection wizard, i.e. what subsystems are advertised for a given systemType in the wizard by default. But for any connection, users should be able to add any services / subsystmes later on dynamically if they want, even if the static association is not there.

(In reply to comment #12) > But nowadays, we have some "standard" subsystems which work against any TCP/IP > connection (ftp, ssh, others in the future). For these, the systemType should > be able to specify what subsystems it can deal with - see bug 173265. In > addition to the static association, the association of systemType <-> subsystem > should also be possible at runtime even if no static association in plugin.xml > is there. Users should be able to choose what subsystems they think are > compatible with their systemType, even without the static association.
Completely agree, as it is necessary for service discovery, where initially it is not possible knowing the services that will be available, so they have to be added at runtime.
> But for any connection, users should be able to add any > services / subsystmes later on dynamically if they want, even if the static > association is not there.
Also, this change will allow actions such as "refresh" to update the services available in a remote system.

Javier/Martin, I've added the following methods to SystemRegistry:
- 2 new createHost() methods to allow you to create a host without creating subsystems.
- createSubSystems() that allows you to pass in subsystem configurations for subsystems that you want to create for a given host. The host can be of any given system type. So we should no longer have static association between system types and subsystem configurations (and by extension subsystems). I'll leave it up to Javier to decide whether to put all discovered services in a host of "Discovery" system type, or to ask the user for the system type (probably a separate discussion).
I'm also looking to add a method to remove a subsystem from a given host. It will be a method in SystemRegistry, probably called deleteSubSystem() with appropriate parameters. These should allow for runtime additions/removals of subsystems from a given host.
Is everyone ok with these changes?
Can you provide a patch, so we can evaluate the functionality ?

(In reply to comment #14) > - createSubSystems() that allows you to pass in subsystem configurations for > subsystems that you want to create for a given host. The host can be of any > given system type. So we should no longer have static association between > system types and subsystem configurations (and by extension subsystems). I'll > leave it up to Javier to decide whether to put all discovered services in a > host of "Discovery" system type, or to ask the user for the system type > (probably a separate discussion).
A "Discovery" system type already exists. I tried after creating the host adding a new subsystem configurations and it doesn't work. The test code is like:
SystemRegistry registry = RSEUIPlugin.getDefault().getSystemRegistry(); IHost conn = registry.createHost("Discovery", "name", "name", "description"); ISubSystemConfiguration sub = registry.getSubSystemConfiguration("ftp.files"); registry.createSubSystems(conn, new ISubSystemConfiguration[]{sub});
From my point of view, it should create a Discovery host adding dynamically a ftp subsystem. Instead it creates 2 empty Discovery hosts in the Remote System view.
Is there anything wrong in my code or can you provide a working example of dynamically adding a subsystem to a host ?
Javier, please try it now. There was a bug that made multiple instances of the same connection show up in RSE.

Now I'm able to create a host and add dynamic subsystems to it, but the host seems not be persisted, as after restarting Eclipse the host disappears.
Can you reproduce it ?

The DOM importer needed to change to restore the subsystem correctly. I've also changed the signature of the createSubSystems() method in ISystemRegistry to return an array of the created subsystems. Subsystems should be persisted correctly through workbench sessions.
Returning as fixed.
Verified, since it's possible creating a host and adding subsystems dynamically.

bug.short_desc: [Editor] Provide better feedback and improve responsivness when opening large files

long_desc.thetext: Currently all the user sees is an hourglass cursor, with no way of knowing what is going on or cancel the operation. Also, because the EMF model is built in the UI thread, the workbench window (the menu bar for example)is not repainted properly while the model is being loaded.

Created an attachment (id=46858) Proposed patch
This patch wraps schema.setElement() into a IRunnableWithProgress operation. This operation is executed using IProgressService.busyCursorWhile.
The standard behaviour for small files is to show just the busy cursor. For schemas with many directives, the operation is long running and a progress dialog is displayed showing the name of the schema file being loaded.
Even though the dialog has a cancel button, the code does not respond to it being pressed as the XSD Schema model is in total control and does not check for the progress monitor cancellation status.
I think this patch is appropriate given the constraints for 1.5.1. We may want to investigate a different approach for 2.0 if needed.
This is a good improvement. Thanks for fixing this! Committed the patch and I'll release shortly.
Verified with M-1.5.1-200609221939
Closing.

bug.short_desc: Error while creating web services with JBoss 4.0.4.GA

long_desc.thetext:
When creating a web project, with a class "Hello" and a simple method "sayHello", and try to make a web service with it, web services wizard appear. I have choose JBoss 4.0.4.GA for server, ask for a test client, and clic next. bug.short_desc: [Editor] Provide better feedback and improve responsivness when opening large files

long_desc.thetext: Currently all the user sees is an hourglass cursor, with no way of knowing what is going on or cancel the operation. Also, because the EMF model is built in the UI thread, the workbench window (the menu bar for example)is not repainted properly while the model is being loaded.

Created an attachment (id=46860) Model patch

Adds a new string resource. Adds a new constant WSDL_PROGRESS_MONITOR to WSDLResourceImpl to allow clients to reuse the name of the option used to pass in a progress monitor. Modifies three other public static "constants" to public static final as they should be.

Created an attachment (id=46861) Editor patch
Apply to wst.wsdl.ui
This patch wraps definition.setElement() into a IRunnableWithProgress operation. This operation is executed using IProgressService.busyCursorWhile.
The standard behaviour for small files is to show just the busy cursor. For definitions with many imports (WSDL or schema), the operation is potentially long running and a progress dialog is displayed showing the name of the WSDL/schema file being loaded.

bug.short_desc: Resolve test execution histories based on GUID

long_desc.thetext:
There's a real need to find execution histories based on GUID in the reporting infrastructure. This is explained below.
One of the fundamental problems with the report generation is resource management. To my knowledge there is a "weak" link between test suites and test execution histories. This link is established in two steps by the report runtime.
1. The report runtime searches the filesystem for files based on a naming convention. For example, if the test suite name is "MyTests" the runtime searches for files that start with "MyTests". 2. Once the list of files are found the files are loaded. A check is performed to verify that the test execution is associated with the test suite.
Notice that this search algorithm breaks down if the test execution histories do not follow this naming convention.
This is the reason why the junit test execution histories are not picked up for each test suite. The junit test execution history follow a different naming convention. The test execution history prepend the package name and name of the test suite.
A patch suggested by Marius in Bug #129031 would solve this problem.
Jerome please assign this bug to me.
Tests are not resolved by guuid instead of test execution file name.

bug.short_desc: Allow multiple levels of LTW information

long_desc.thetext:
It would be nice if basic information about load-time weaving (what version of AspectJ is being used, what loaders are doing weaving and what configuration is being used) was available without all of the -verbose information listing of all classes woven or not woven.
It's also unfortunate that the flags for weaving level are 2 quite different ones: -Daj.weaving.verbose -Dorg.aspectj.weaver.showWeaveInfo
Why not something like -Dorg.aspectj.weaver.level=[none|summary|info|verbose]
summary: just what configuration is used info: list affected join points etc. (like showWeaveInfo) verbose: all (like verbose now)

I assume you would always like warnings and errors to come out? In which case they need context i.e. what aspects are registered and which aop.xml files were used. Therefore I think it makes sense to put out what you call "summary" information by default. Perhaps a better approach would be -silent which (for whatever reason) allows a user to turn of all messages. The -verbose and showWeaveInfo options, which of cause are not peculiar to LTW, would remain the same.
The aop.xml file will remain the primary configuration mechanism because in a complex system it is easier to use than System properties (in my experience) and has none of the security implications. However we should revisit the names used as they are quite old. I suspect org.aspectj.weaver.loadtime.XXX would be a good start.

Another option would be for many of the current info messages in LTW to be debug. We don't seem to use this level of messages at the moment so their is no support for a -debug flag but it would be consistent with other tools like Ant. So that way we would have: default: warning, error -verbose: info including AspectJ version, classloader, configuration -showWeaveInfo: weave -debug: debug including weaving, not weaving, generating, ...
We could also keep the initial configuration messages and dump them when we get the first warning or error for context.

I would definitely like errors to come out. I would like to be able to configure warnings to suppress known ones but otherwise they should too. I quite like the idea of dumping configuration information when an error or warning is emitted. The other case where configuration information is helpful to see is when nothing is happening (e.g., -javaagent isn't being passed in, the aop.xml file isn't present, possibly one aop.xml file turns off something in another one: that is a possible warning itself).
I would also be quite happy with some kind of log adapter so that AspectJ messages could be configured through normal logging mechanisms. I agree that configuring anything possible within the aop.xml file is the preferred place: the one place where system-wide flags make sense is for global configuration (e.g., troubleshooting if you have set up your aop configuration correctly).
-Dorg.aspectj.weaver.loadtime.XXX sounds good to me, and the levels sound right. I would suggest leaving -verbose as a deprecated alias for -debug:
default: warning, error -info: info including AspectJ version, classloader, configuration -showWeaveInfo: weave PLUS info -debug: debug including weaving, not weaving, generating, ... PLUS showWeaveInfo -verbose: same as -debug with deprecated warning message (or not)
How hard would it be to allow plugging in a log message handler instead of writing to the console? It seems like this is a good area to define a Plugin API with a simple interface so people can create adapters for Log4J, RAS, JULI/jdk, commons logging, sl4j, etc.

>I would like to be able to configure warnings to suppress known ones but >otherwise they should too. I will ask the same question as I did for Xlint: which warnings do you feel the need to suppress? The product should work out of the box if coding guidelines are followed. The messages are there for me as well as you :-)
>e.g., -javaagent isn't being passed in, Im not sure how we can handle this one as we are not in the loop at all
>the aop.xml file isn't present, possibly one aop.xml file turns off >something in another one: that is a possible warning itself We already list the aop.xml files that are used. Using include/exclude for aspects can cause aspectExcludedByConfiguration to be issued. We already issue not woven messages (which should probably be debug) but I could add a reason why a class is exluded
>How hard would it be to allow plugging in a log message handler instead >of writing to the console? Probably not very. Andy and I have been talking about problem diagnosis for LTW. I have just opened Bug 150487 Tracing and Logging Framework.
With the growing popularity of load-time weaving it is becoming increasing difficult to diagnose complex problems given the limited diagnostic information available: stack trace, verbose output, and dumped byte-code. With compiler errors it is usually possible for the bug raiser to attach a testcase but this is not possible when the problem may concern environment or integration with middleware. I therefore propose we implement a tracing/logging mechanism that will capture low level entry/exit information as well as existing informational messages (see Rons comment in Bug 150271 Allow multiple levels of LTW information) and route them to one of the existing logging infrastructures such as JDK 1.4 or Jakarta Commons logging.

>I will ask the same question as I did for Xlint: which warnings do you feel the >need to suppress? The product should work out of the box if coding guidelines >are followed. The messages are there for me as well as you :-)
Almost any of the warnings that are reasonable to suppress today have been made configurable through Xlint, which is good. As an example of something of the sort, suppose there's a runtime limitation like not being able to inline around advice because of the aspect configuration (e.g., shared library aspects from the system classpath aren't being woven). That should be a warning, but it should also be supressable. The system may well work just fine without inlined around advice and an administrator shouldn't have to see a warning about it if the developer realizes the limitation and has tested for it. This wouldn't be a weaver issue since it's really an LTW configuration warning, so I don't think it should go in Xlint.properties. But that one is hypothetical. A quick look through the loadtime module shows a few other candidates: * warnings for missing DTD's (dumped directly to syserr in DocumentParser) * define generated class failed (ClassLoaderWeavingAdaptor): as noted in the code, there might be situtations where this happens but it's not an error. There may also be systems that recover properly from a runtime limitation like this and don't want it emitted to the output.
Of course the current aop.xml mechanism does allow you to suppress warnings, but unfortunately it suppresses all of them. I think only a few should be suppressable, based on analysis that indicates it might be expected to run with the warning occurring, rather than it being a problem that should always be fixed.
>>e.g., -javaagent isn't being passed in, >Im not sure how we can handle this one as we are not in the loop at all
The best way to test for this is a simple output to indicate that the LTW system has started with the AspectJ version. I.e., without any configuration, did the system print something? I'd be glad to have that one line of information come out (e.g., at INFO level in a log) by default unless you start with a silent flag.
>...I could add a reason why a class is exluded That sounds good for debug purposes.
Re: bug #150487, that sounds great. Thanks for creating that!

I was hoping for a list of existing warnings that you felt the need to suppress rather that a list of new ones that if I added you would like to be able suppress. As with Bug 149322 Change Xlint cantFindType default to warning I believe warnings and errors should not be suppressed as a matter of course. If there are situations when a change to your code cannot remove the warning/error but you feel the resulting application behaves correctly then we should review the message.
Lets discuss the new ones you mentioned: - Not being able to inline around advice: I believe warnings should be used to help people. If the compiler issues a warning which the user can do nothing about, as in this situation, apart from suppress it then the message is pointless. I have opened Bug 149802 Support inlining of all eligible around advice to investigate whether we can apply the optimization more widely. - warnings for missing DTD's: This should be an error, not even Xlint. - define generated class failed: This should also be an error. I was nervous about making it one because certain message handles abort on errors. There is not a situation that I can think of where not being able to define a closure on which a class we have just woven has a hard dependency is OK. I dont agree with the comment in the code. We should either ignore the explicit case mentioned or stop the situation occurring (it might be related to Bug 119657 IllegalAccessError with around advice on interface method call).

There aren't any other cases of warnings that I've encountered that I might like to suppress other than Xlint warnings and the two examples I listed. There might be some others that I've not encountered, but if there are they're either rare or not relevant to configurations I've used.

> ...I might like to suppress other than Xlint warnings Which ones? I don't think we are explicit enough about the purpose of Xlint but my understanding of the process from conversations the Jim H. is that it is an experimental area rather than a generalized process for suppressing errors/warnings. When I add an Xlint error I do so because I feel I might break a user who cannot avoid it. When we understand the situation better either the message goes away or becomes a hard error.

Here are the Xlint properties that default to warning that I have been suppressing:
invalidAbsoluteTypeName [needed to support optional 3rd party libraries] typeNotExposedToWeaver [needed to support optional 3rd party libraries] unmatchedSuperTypeInCall [these are of course valid and intended to not match] adviceDidNotMatch [ditto] runtimeExceptionNotSoftened [I don't want to soften runtime exceptions]
Of course cantFindType/cantFindTypeAffectingJPMatch are the subject of a different bugzilla issue.

I have gone for the approach in Comment #2 although there is not yet support for dumping configuration information by default at the first error. This should reduce the amount of output generated when just trying to obtain configuration information.
>Why not something like -Dorg.aspectj.weaver.level=[none|summary|info|verbose] Unfortunately we don't yet have the concept of "levels": weaveInfo is completely separate although you coud imagine: default(warning & error), -verbose(info), -debug(debug) -showWeaveInfo(weaveInfo) with one automatically including those above. Of course this only applies to the default WeavingAdaptorMessageWriter and you are free to supply you own.

>... A quick look >through the loadtime module shows a few other candidates: >* warnings for missing DTD's (dumped directly to syserr in DocumentParser)
Are you referring to DocumentParser. resolveEntity() in which case do you have a situation where this arised so that I can write a test. Or are you referring to this type of Exception which is thrown for badly formed aop.xml and for which we issue a warning (not error) but the stack trace is dumped by default:
[AppClassLoader@9627532] warning parse definitions failed -- (SAXParseException) The element type "concrete-aspect" must be terminated by the matching end-tag "</concrete-aspect>". The element type "concrete-aspect" must be terminated by the matching end-tag "</concrete-aspect>". org.xml.sax.SAXParseException: The element type "concrete-aspect" must be terminated by the matching end-tag "</concrete-aspect>". at com.sun.org.apache.xerces.internal.util.ErrorHandlerWrapper.createSAXParseException(ErrorHandlerWrapper.java:236) at com.sun.org.apache.xerces.internal.util.ErrorHandlerWrapper.fatalError(ErrorHandlerWrapper.java:215) at com.sun.org.apache.xerces.internal.impl.XMLErrorReporter.reportError(XMLErrorReporter.java:386)

I was indeed referring to DocumentParser.resolveEntity. I believe you could trigger one warning by writing an aop.xml file with an unknown DTD (e.g., -//AspectJ//DTD 1.5.3//EN). The other one would be hard to test: you'd need a configuration where the weaving agent is unable to read the aspectj_1_5_0.dtd resource (which would be a broken one!)
I noticed these warnings from reviewing the code when you asked what other warnings might need to be supressed. But in general, neither of these two warnings should be suppressed. If we add another version of the DTD then the weaver should continue to be backwards-compatible and support the old ones...
Leaving this one for now until after I have investigated the use of ajcore for FFDC.

bug.short_desc: [Key Bindings] Cross-platform differences problematic

long_desc.thetext:
I use a Mac at home and a Windows PC at work. I refactor a lot, from the keyboard, and the finger-position differences (sometimes even the finger-count differences) make this part of the interface very visible, and very irritating.
It's great that you've reserved modifer key pairs for refactoring - that it's refactoring-modifier-keys-M to extract a method, and refactoring-modifer-keys-L to create a local variable, etc. - but the finger positions are pinkie-thumb for Windows' shift-alt, and fat-thumb-overlapping for Mac's option-command (I think I've got that right; I have Windows in front of me at the moment). And then mixing it up with Run Last Launched - which I also use a great deal, on Windows it's ctrl-F11, and on the Mac it's (I think) shift-command-F11, so the modifier fingers I use for Refactoring on Windows give me Run Last Launched on the Mac. And then there's goofy stuff like using command-arrow to advance a (partial) word on the Mac, where command-arrow means end-of-line, and I can't remember whether End works (maybe?).
The point of keyboard shortcuts is to save time and energy, and these shortcuts are really not doing that for me. If I were consistently on one platform, I'd get used to it, but back and forth is really a bear.
I don't have any solutions to propose, I'm sorry to say - I just want you to know that this aspect of Eclipse is bugging me. Eclipse is great; I want this part of it to be just as great. Thanks.
Unfortunatly it isn't easy anymore for us to change the default key bindings. Too many users would complain. So I recommend you to just configure and optimize them for yourself in your workspace.

bug.short_desc: Flicker with the new WinXP border with scroll bars

long_desc.thetext: The new XP-ish blue border on Composites flickers, sometimes significantly. It almost appears like the older non-XP border is drawn first, then the new XP border is drawn over top (but maybe thats only in my mind).

"It almost appears like the older non-XP border is drawn first, then the new XP border is drawn over top (but maybe thats only in my mind)."
That is exactly what happens! SWT needs to call the windowproc for wm_ncpaint to draw the non-client part of the window (borders and scrollbars), people don't like the old 3-d border look, so after it returns from the windowproc SWT draws the xp look border on top of the old border.
Steve, any idea how to fix this ? clipping maybe ?
This has already been fixed for a while.
Is it fixed in 3.2.1 or 3.3?
Is there any chance we can get this fix into the 3.2.1 codebase?
Can you verify that the 3.3 SWT code in HEAD fixes the flickering you are seeing?

This is definitely not fixed in the 3.3 M1. I attempted to test with the HEAD SWT (3306), but I apparently lack the skills to update just the SWT portion of my 3.3M1. I replaced the DLLs and Eclipse itself ran fine, but my RCP test application now dies from deep workbench errors. Maybe I'll wait a few weeks and see if we can get a stable nightly build.
Making a stand alone SWT snippet (like Main2) is trivial. Can you make one that uses the widget that is failing in your RCP application? If the bug is not fixed, it should be reopened.
So should I make a separate bug entry to handle the specific flicker issue concerning a Canvas with scrollbars?
Nope.
