bug.short_desc: Need to pass export path into data exporters

long_desc.thetext:
There is currently no way for a data exporter to know where it is exporting data. This renders it impossible to add special information such as images and other data not directly exportable by the analysis data model.
For example an HTML exporter needs to be able write the rule icons into the export output directory so they can be referenced by the generated HTMl file. This is currently not possible and as a result is impacting several users writing cusomt exporters.
Added code to the export path and file name into the interface and added support for HTML export
closed

bug.short_desc: associate plugins with task repositories and products

long_desc.thetext:
An extension point along the following lines would allow for automatic component selection (e.g. for bug 135605):
<extension point="org.eclipse.mylar.tasks.repositories"> <bugRepository connector="bugzilla" product="Mylar"/> </extension>

Hmm. Should it have repository url too? I also recall there was an issue opened for linking Eclipse projects to the repositories tht was also suggestin some pluggable relolution mehanisms. E.g. one could use Maven data and search trough stack trace and link package names to product artifacts and extract issue tracking system location from Maven's poms for those artifcats.
Yes, URL should be there too (e.g. helping support generic web Connector). Linking to projects is related (bug 145214).

Balazs: could you make this your next priority? The Welcome stuff is great, but this would be really helpful to have in 2.0 along with the related updates to bug 183606. Please let me know if you would like some pointers about how we use and create extension points. This one would go into ..mylar.tasks.ui/schema/repositories.exsd
*** Bug 152420 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***

An extension point may not be the right way of doing this, because it does not support the producer/consumer separation. For example, an Eclipse-based product may want to handle all bug reports made against Platform in order to ensure response time. For this reason I think that the mapping would best be specified in an external resource (e.g. a plug-in to tracker/product mapping file), and could provide support for things like wildcard matching (e.g. all Errors from package org.eclipse.mylyn.jira.* plug-ins should be logged to repository foo). EPP distros could then specify bugs.eclispe.org, with appropriate product/component mappings, but redistributions would be free to do their own thign. Syntax could be something like:
pluginPattern="org.eclispe.mylyn.jira.*" repository="https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs" attributes="Product=Mylyn;Component=Jira;Version=2.1"

Mik, we really need to support project/product and component/module at the task model. Also, I believe this metadata about component mapping could came from other sources, so it should be possible to plug custom adapter from that information instead/in addition to reading it from proprietary files.

Eugene: it would be nice if we could standardize on project/product and component/module, but we currently support connectors that have no notion of that. For example, an agile project management tool might only use the following attributes:
attributes="Kind=Defect;Version=1.0;"
We could consider having an optional product= and component= mapping, and having the repository connector specify what that maps to, if appropriate, but this is not for sure an overall win. It would be a win for many Bugzilla and JIRA installs though, and similar bug/issue trackers, so we can consider it.

(In reply to comment #7) > Eugene: it would be nice if we could standardize on project/product and > component/module, but we currently support connectors that have no notion of > that. For example, an agile project management tool might only use the > following attributes: > > attributes="Kind=Defect;Version=1.0;"
I don't see how those are useful for mapping to products. Besides, we have 3 or even 4 Mylyn's reference connectors that have notion of project/product and module.
> We could consider having an optional product= and component= mapping, and having > the repository connector specify what that maps to, if appropriate, but this is > not for sure an overall win. It would be a win for many Bugzilla and JIRA > installs though, and similar bug/issue trackers, so we can consider it.
Exactly. We are missing this component/project mapping not only for this purpose. I can think of a dozen of other places when that would be useful.

bug.short_desc: Restore instead of Restore Defaults?

long_desc.thetext: The Targeted Runtimes project properties page has a Restore button instead of the standard Restore Defaults button. For consistency it should be labelled the same as all the other pages.

That's intentional. There is no such thing as defaults for the target runtimes. The Restore button resets the panel state to what's currently in the project. That is the state that it was in before user made any changes.

Things like Info, Javadoc location, Server, or J2EE Module Dependancies don't have true defaults either, but they all use the standard text. If you think the platform has this wrong, you should work with the platform or other teams to fix it instead of making facets "correct" but inconsistent with everything else.

It's not the question of which label is right. It's a question of semantics. The Restore button on the Targeted Runtimes property page does not have the same semantics as the Restore Defaults button on the pages you've mentioned.
The Restore Defaults button wipes the slate and sets the configuration to what it would have been when a new project is created. That is, if you open a project properties page hit the Restore Defaults button and then apply, you are likely changing the state of the project. That is not the case with the Restore button on the Runtimes panel. If you open that property page and hit Restore, nothing will happen. If you make some changes and then hit Restore, you will be taken back to the no-op state. That is, you will never be making changes to the project if you hit Restore prior to hitting Apply.

(In reply to comment #3) > That is not the case with the Restore > button on the Runtimes panel. If you open that property page and hit Restore, > nothing will happen. If you make some changes and then hit Restore, you will be > taken back to the no-op state. That is, you will never be making changes to the > project if you hit Restore prior to hitting Apply.
I'm confused, isn't this then just duplicating functionality provided by the Cancel button for the entire dialog?

Yes, you could get the same behavior by canceling and re-opening the dialog, but that's a couple of extra steps. The scenario is someone going down the wrong track and wanting to retrace steps back to the prior state.

Kosta - That's the exact same semantics as the Javadoc location, how the J2EE Module Dependancies page works in some scenarios, or the "New text file..." option in the Info page. It's not a unique usage scenario.
Nitin - In this case yes, although the Restore lets you continue to make changes. So if you mess up the settings you can hit restore and try again instead of cancelling and reopening.

In which case, there is bigger platform-wide problem of inconsistent semantics employed for the Restore Defaults button from page to page. To see what my understanding of the intended semantics is, take a look at the Java Compiler properties page.
Are you arguing that having buttons with the same label produce different behaviors is better than having different labels for different behaviors?

Ok. Since the behavior of Restore Defaults seems to be already inconsistent across the platform, my original fear of overloading the Restore Default semantics seems unfounded. I will go ahead and change the label from Restore to Restore Defaults.
Released the change to 1.5.1 and 2.0 streams.
Closing.

bug.short_desc: [prefs] Should avoid messages printed to the console

long_desc.thetext:
Actually, why would the debugTracker ever be null. It should not matter if we are in dev mode or not. The debugTracker is always set to a ServiceTracker object when preferences is started.
The only way it could be null is if the EclipsePreferences class is loaded before the startlevel of the preferences bundle is reached. This would prevent the preferences bundle from starting on the first classload which means the activator would not be run before the static initializer code in EclipsePreferences is run.
So to answer your question DJ. The Jobs code is correct because the debugTracker should never be null if the jobs bundle is lazy started.

You can consistently cause the messages to appear if you using the command arguments
-console -plugincustomization foo
The issue is in the Activator we call processCommandLine before calling PreferencesOSGiUtils.getDefault().openServices()
This causes DefaultPreferences which extends EclipsePreferences to load before the debugTracker can be initialized. DJ, can you simply change the order of these calls in the Activator?
+1 for 3.2.1 assuming that hte fix is easy.
Fixed in HEAD. Marking as 3.2.1 but leaving bug open until I get my 3.2.1 workspace up and the code released.
Released to 3.2.x.

bug.short_desc: extract headless frameworks

long_desc.thetext:
To support running Mylar headless we need to extract the current frameworks. Here is a proposed refactoring. Note that bridges (e.g. org.eclipse.mylar.bridge.ide) and connectors are not named as such because that seems obvious enoug and bloats the package names. The org.eclipse.mylar.context.core name seems a bit long, especially with .provisional and .internal appended, but it helps distinguishing the Context framework from the Task framework.
org.eclipse.mylar-feature (Task Management) - org.eclipse.mylar.tasks.core (headless framework) was in mylar.tasklist - org.eclipse.mylar.tasks.ui (tasklist, task activity) was mylar.tasklist
org.eclipse.mylar.ide-feature (Focused UI) - org.eclipse.mylar.context.core (headless framework, context, writers) was mylar.core - org.eclipse.mylar.context.ui (filters, content outline, active search) - org.eclipse.mylar.resources (resources, markers, editors) - org.eclipse.mylar.team (change sets and version control) - org.eclipse.mylar.ide (navigator, problems, pde, ant, cvs) - org.eclipse.mylar.java (jdt, junit)
org.eclipse.mylar.bugzilla-feature (Bugzilla Connector) - org.eclipse.mylar.bugzilla.core (runs headless) - org.eclipse.mylar.bugzilla.ui (UI)
org.eclipse.mylar.monitor-feature (Usage monitor) - org.eclipse.mylar.monitor (UI framework)
Nearly done, just a few startup concurrency problems left to resolve. Should be committed Thursday AM.

First round of changes committed, still some package renaming to be done, and waiting on webmaster for rename. CVS tag before refactoring is R_0_6_0_prerefactoring. I'll post here and then send a message with details to mylar-dev when done.

-create a query against a repository (by url) -use task synchronization code to keep all tasks in this query up to date -- this might want to be automated, but not a crucial part of the system at the moment. -examine a listing of attachments on a bug report (user who submitted, attachment id, attachment description [ie: mylar/context/zip] ) -download attachments (contexts in particular)

bug.short_desc: eclipse.org should release the build system for Eclipse and other products as a complete, working system in a VMware image

long_desc.thetext:
Trying to get continuous development going with Eclipse projects is rough. I've been through many articles and streams-of-consciousness snippets.
Have you considered releasing the whole kit-and-kaboodle as a VM appliance (including CVS, Continuum, Maven, whatever you guys are currently using and advocating as a build system for RCP and Eclipse 3.2 itself)?
It would be a boon to all if one could just download and run on the free VMware server product. To some it would be a working template and guide as to how to tweak their existing infrastructure but to most I would suspect it would be a complete solution to just get going without derailing over build systems for a while.

Are you referring to the eclipse platform build system? It's not really that simple. It's a lot of scripts and about 12 machines that are used to run the platform builds. Each project under the eclipse.org umbrella uses a variation of this build process or something completely different.
If you are interested in learning more about the pde build, this is a good starting point
http://help.eclipse.org/help32/index.jsp?topic=/org.eclipse.pde.doc.user/guide/tasks/pde_feature_build.htm
Closing, won't fix.

bug.short_desc: [hotbug][project explorer] Deployment Descriptor model lost on project copy

long_desc.thetext:
When using the Eclipse project copy operation on a J2EE project (web, ejb, ear), the copied project's deployment descriptor model is not being properly set up. In the J2EE perspective Project Explorer view, the copied project's deployment descriptor element doesn't show up. Also, any validators which access the deployment descriptor fail. For example, on a copied web project, the validator fails with CHKJ3000E: WAR Validation Failed: error.org.eclipse.jst.j2ee.commonarchivecore.internal.exception.DeploymentDescriptorLoadException: WEB-INF/web.xml
Can recreate in the project explorer using the Copy / Paste project actions, and can also recreate programmatically through IResource.copy().
Closing and re-opening the project causes the deployment descriptor model to properly show up. Validation can then be forced (doesn't automatically occur) by touching the deployment descriptor, in order to remove the validation errors caused by absence of the descriptor.

Created an attachment (id=46946) Corrects the nature_registration for ModuleCoreNature
When the project is c&p'd, the Project Resource Set is not properly configured before the resource change listeners are notified. This results in resources being created before the resource factories are configured properly, which results in load difficulties later on.
This patch corrects the nature_registration extension so that the ModuleCoreNature will have an opportunity to contribute to the EMFWorkbenchContext (and thus configure the URI converters and Resource Factories properly before any resources are created).
John -- would you review and release this patch. Thanks.
This is released for the WTP 1.5.1 builds for 073006.

From testing under WTP M-1.5.1-200608110237, there are still problems copying a J2EE project, regarding loss of the deployment descriptor, however now the deployment descriptor from the original project is adversely affected instead of the copy. After the copy / paste operation, the project copy has a proper deployment descriptor, but the original project's deployment descriptor either disappears from the Project Explorer view, or if it is present, attempting to open it for editing results in the following: - the editor comes up with the descriptor marked with the "changed" asterisk (even though no changes have been made through the editor) - saving the descriptor from the editor results in an org.eclipse.jst.j2ee.commonarchivecore.internal.exception being logged - closing the editor without saving the descriptor results in other exceptions being logged, and the descriptor no longer appears in the Project Explorer view. bug.short_desc: [ICU] Move to new version of ICU4J containing ICU critical performance fix [Bug 5203]

long_desc.thetext:
Using the ICU4J classes (com.ibm.icu.text.SimpleDataFormat and Timezone)for creating timestamps leads to significant performance degradation. Replacing with java.text.SimpleDataFormat improves the performance with 240%. ICU4J defect: http://bugs.icu-project.org/cgi-bin/icu-bugs/incoming?findid=5203 ------------------------------------------------------------------------------ From Ram Viswanadha:
Raghuram Viswanadha/San Jose/IBM@IBMUS 30/06/2006 02:15 PM To Uliyana Markova/Toronto/IBM@IBMCA cc Christine Knight/Toronto/IBM@IBMCA, Eric Labadie/Toronto/IBM@IBMCA, Paul Slauenwhite/Toronto/IBM@IBMCA, Robert Geiger/Cranford/IBM@IBMUS, Andy Heninger/San Jose/IBM@IBMUS, Yoshito Umaoka/Westford/IBM@LOTUS Subject Re: Fw: ICU4J performance issue - defect # 5203
Hi Uliyana, > Can you please tell me when is the earliest a newer version of ICU4J should be expected that will contain the performance problem fix? The release target date for ICU4J 3.6 is 1st of October, 2006. We do not have a good estimate of time it would take to fix the performance issues. Our DateFormat expert has left IBM, so it would take some time for me or another team member to get up to speed with the code and figure out the performance bottlenecks. Moreover, our team has been cut in half due to sudden attrition and we are scrambling to get 3 products (ICU4C, ICU4J and ICU4JNI) out of the door.
> Also, please confirm that a newer version is indeed the only way and no patch can be provided to fix his issue. I am trying to understand the constraints to give you a clear indication of future course of action. Your schedule is one of the main constraints. If your deadline is around the release of ICU4J 3.6 then it does not make sense for us to spend cycles releasing another version of ICU4J. Please let us know your dates and we will work with you get a maintenance release done to meet your deadline if needed.
Best Regards,
Ram -------------------------------- Ram Viswanadha e-mail: ramv@us.ibm.com tel#: (408) 956-3318 IBM GCoC - San Jose 4400 North First St, Suite 100, San Jose CA - 95134
This is a request to have ICU4J 3.6 included in the 3.2.1 release.

This email from Karice captures the constraints from the Eclipse team's pov:
From the Platform's perspective, the sooner a new version of ICU4J is in the builds the better. However, there are a couple of problems I see with the proposed solution for Eclipse 3.2.1 as it stands right now:
1. If ICU4J 3.6 introduces new APIs then the platform cannot accept this version for inclusion in 3.2.1, since new APIs are not allowed in maintenance releases. Andy or Yoshito can let us know whether or not ICU4J 3.6 will have new API (compared to ICU4J3.4.4).
2. ICU's ship date for 3.6 is *after* the Eclipse 3.2.1 ship date. The only way we could accept ICU4J3.6 is if the ICU team can guarantee the code that is released for ICU4J 3.6 is the same as what we would have in the ICU4J plugin they submit to us. Though this seems possible in theory since their ship date is only 2 days after ours, in reality the platform cannot take the risk of accepting new ICU4J code for inclusion in 3.2.1 in the last 2 weeks before the ship date, to maintain stability in the platform.
A safer alternative (from the platform's perspective) is for the ICU team to produce a maintenance version of the ICU4J plug-in (say 3.4.4.2 ?) with only the code that fixes the performance problem - so it would be based on ICU4J 3.4.4.1 code (Eclipse has a special version of ICU4J, 3.4.4.1, based on ICU4J 3.4.4). That decision is completely up to the ICU team, obviously, but I can say that the platform is much more likely to accept a maintenance version of ICU4J into Eclipse 3.2.1, provided it is submitted at least 2 weeks in advance of the 3.2.1 deadline.

Update: The ICU team has agreed to do a 3.4.5 version of ICU4J for Eclipse 3.2.1. This will also be released as a public version on the ICU site. The platform can accept this version pending requirements for JUnit tests (all pass), legal (files, approval, etc), and general stability are met and as long as it is provided in a reasonable time frame (I have heard from Yoshito that they want to ship it in the next couple of weeks).

ICU4J 3.4.5 was received this week, but needs to be re-spun as it was not built correctly (had some out of date legal files, incorrect version numbers used, and some code is missing from the replacement plug-in). Still pending approval from Eclipse PMC and Eclipse Foundation.

The final revision of ICU4J 3.4.5 was received last Thursday (Aug 24th) with all required files for the bundles generated correctly and properly updated. It is set to be included in the Platform's M-build (for 3.2.1) this Wednesday. Once I have confirmed it is in the M-build, I will mark this bug as fixed.
ICU4J 3.4.5 is in the M20060830-0800 build
Closing the bug.

bug.short_desc: AC/RAC cannot translation properly

long_desc.thetext:
TPTP 4.2.0 has been translated. A special packaging has been created for the RAC. However, Samson said that AC and RAC cannot handle the NL packages properly.
Here is the statement from Samson: I have just checked that the current AC/RAC cannot handle the NL zips properly. - The config generator (SetConfig) can only pickup config.nl1.jar but none of the nl2's. This is becase nl2 was not in the discussion last time when we talked about config generator changes. - None of the plugin's nl1, nl2 and nl2a jars are being picked up since 1) when version numbers does not match the base plugin, and 2) the nl2a jar name is not known by the config generator. It only knowns about nl1, nl2 without the "a" at the end.
Is there a way to make sure the version numbers are matched? It may be cause my base TPTP driver is a little bit older than the NL ones. As long as we can have them matched there should be no problem for nl1 and nl2 files. For nl2a we will need a code change in the config generator, or perhaps combining nl2a with nl2 without any code change.

Thay tested this successfully on Windows and LinuxX86 exercising nl1, nl2, nl2a locales.

long_desc.thetext:
